an-related television programs]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in England]]\n", "name_user": "JHunterJ", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up, replaced: 4 million \u2192 4\u00a0million", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Holby_City"}
{"title_page": "Kevlin Henney", "text_new": "{{multiple issues|\n{{notability|Biographies|date=November 2018}}\n{{unreliable sources|date=November 2018}}\n{{BLP primary sources|date=November 2018}}\n}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2018}}{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2018}}\n'''Kevlin Henney''' is an author, presenter, and consultant on software development. He has written on the subject of [[computer programming]] and development practice for many magazines and sites, including ''Better Software'', ''[[The Register]]'', ''[[C/C++ Users Journal]]'', ''Application Development Advisor'', ''JavaSpektrum'', ''[[C++ Report]]'', ''Java Report'', ''[[.EXE Magazine|EXE]]'', and ''[[Overload (journal)|Overload]]''. He is a member of the [[Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers|IEEE]] Software Advisory Board. Henney is also coauthor of books on patterns and editor of ''97 Things Every Programmer Should Know''.\n\nHenney has given [[keynote]] addresses at a number of conferences, including ''Agile'', [[Association of C and C Plus Plus Users|ACCU]], [[DevTernity Conference|DevTernity]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sizovs.net/2019/09/07/what-to-expect-from-devternity-2019/|title=What to expect from DevTernity 2019?|last=Sizovs|first=Eduards|website=sizovs.net|language=en|access-date=2020-01-04}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=Kevlin Henney - Seven Ineffective Coding Habits of Many Programmers|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SUIUZ09mnwM|volume=|pages=|publication-date=22 December 2016|publisher=DevTernity|language=en|access-date=2020-01-04}}</ref> ''DevWeek'', ''Dutch PHP Conference'', ''Embedded Systems Club'', ''GeeCON'', ''GOTO'', ''Build Stuff'', ''JAOO'', ''JAZOON'', ''Jfokus'', ''NLUUG'', ''OOP'', ''PHPNW'', ''SDC'', ''Software Architect'', ''VOXXEDDAYS'', and ''XP Day''.\n\nHenney is a member of the [[Association of C and C Plus Plus Users|ACCU]], and gave the keynote address at the 2001 ACCU conference<ref name=\"ACCU2001\">{{cite web\n |url          = http://thad.notagoth.org/accu_spring_2001/#minimalism\n |title        = ACCU Spring Conference 2001 Roundup\n |author       = Thaddaeus Frogley\n |work         = Thad's Homepage\n |accessdate   = 2005-11-16\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20080514125419/http://thad.notagoth.org/accu_spring_2001/#minimalism#minimalism\n |archive-date = 14 May 2008\n |url-status     = dead\n |df           = dmy-all\n}}</ref> on the subject of writing less code, because \"there is no code faster than no code\" and \"less code, equals less bugs\" (of which he is an active presenter). He is also a speaker at [[OOPSLA]], most recently speaking at OOPSLA 2005.<ref name=\"OOPSLA2005\">{{cite web|\nurl=http://www.enterpriseintegrationpatterns.com/ramblings/37_oopsla.html|\nwork=Gregor's Ramblings|\ntitle=Revenge of the Nerds \u2013 OOPSLA 2005|\naccessdate=2005-11-16}}\n</ref> In October 2009, Henney presented ''The Uncertainty Principle''<ref name=\"PHPNW09\">[http://conference.phpnw.org.uk/phpnw09/?page_id=7 The Uncertainty Principle, Kevlin Henney, 2nd Annual PHP North West Conference]</ref> at the 2nd Annual PHP North West Conference in Manchester, UK. He has also been credited with the remark \"...except for the problem of too many layers of indirection\"{{citation needed|date=November 2018}} in response to the famous [[aphorism]] of [[David Wheeler (computer scientist)|David Wheeler]]: \"All problems in computer science can be solved by another level of indirection.\"<ref>Diomidis Spinellis.\n[http://www.dmst.aueb.gr/dds/pubs/inbook/beautiful_code/html/Spi07g.html Another level of indirection].\nIn Andy Oram and Greg Wilson, editors,\n''Beautiful Code: Leading Programmers Explain How They Think'', chapter 17, pages 279&ndash;291.\nO'Reilly and Associates, Sebastopol, CA, 2007.\n</ref>\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* {{cite book|\nauthor=Frank Buschmann|\nauthor2=Kevlin Henney|\nauthor3=Douglas C. Schmidt|\nauthor3-link=Douglas C. Schmidt|\ntitle=Pattern-Oriented Software Architecture, Volume 4: A Pattern Language for Distributed Computing|\nisbn=978-0-470-05902-9|\npublisher=John Wiley & Sons|\nyear=2007}}\n* {{cite book|\nauthor=Frank Buschmann|\nauthor2=Kevlin Henney|\nauthor3=Douglas C. Schmidt|\nauthor3-link=Douglas C. Schmidt|\ntitle=Pattern-Oriented Software Architecture, Volume 5: On Patterns and Pattern Languages|\npublisher=John Wiley & Sons|\nisbn=978-0-471-48648-0|\nyear=2007}}\n* {{cite book|\neditor=Kevlin Henney|\ntitle=97 Things Every Programmer Should Know|\npublisher=O'Reilly Media|\nisbn=978-0-596-80948-5|\nyear=2010}}\n* {{cite book|\neditor=Richard Monson-Haefel|\ntitle=97 Things Every Software Architect Should Know|\npublisher=O'Reilly Media|\nisbn=978-0-596-52269-8|\nyear=2009}}\n* {{cite book|\neditor=Kevlin Henney|\ntitle=97 Things Every Java Programmer Should Know|\npublisher=O'Reilly Media|\nisbn=978-1-4919-5269-6|\nyear=2017}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://curbralan.com/ Kevlin Henney's home page], including:\n** [http://www.two-sdg.demon.co.uk/curbralan/papers.html Kevlin Henney's bibliography]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20051222104822/http://accu.informika.ru/accu/bookreviews/public/reviews/0rv/Kevlin_Henney.htm Book Reviews by Kevlin Henney] at the ACCU\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Henney, Kevlin}}\n[[Category:British technology writers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:British software engineers]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n\n{{UK-writer-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{multiple issues|\n{{notability|Biographies|date=November 2018}}\n{{unreliable sources|date=November 2018}}\n{{BLP primary sources|date=November 2018}}\n}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2018}}{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2018}}\n'''Kevlin Henney''' is an author, presenter, and consultant on software development. He has written on the subject of [[computer programming]] and development practice for many magazines and sites, including ''Better Software'', ''[[The Register]]'', ''[[C/C++ Users Journal]]'', ''Application Development Advisor'', ''JavaSpektrum'', ''[[C++ Report]]'', ''Java Report'', ''[[.EXE Magazine|EXE]]'', and ''[[Overload (journal)|Overload]]''. He is a member of the [[Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers|IEEE]] Software Advisory Board. Henney is also coauthor of books on patterns and editor of ''97 Things Every Programmer Should Know''.\n\nHenney has given [[keynote]] addresses at a number of conferences, including ''Agile'', [[Association of C and C Plus Plus Users|ACCU]], [[DevTernity Conference|DevTernity]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sizovs.net/2019/09/07/what-to-expect-from-devternity-2019/|title=What to expect from DevTernity 2019?|last=Sizovs|first=Eduards|website=sizovs.net|language=en|access-date=2020-01-04}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=Kevlin Henney - Seven Ineffective Coding Habits of Many Programmers|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SUIUZ09mnwM|volume=|pages=|publication-date=22 December 2016|publisher=DevTernity|language=en|access-date=2020-01-04}}</ref> ''DevWeek'', ''Dutch PHP Conference'', ''Embedded Systems Club'', ''GeeCON'', ''GOTO'', ''Build Stuff'', ''JAOO'', ''JAZOON'', ''Jfokus'', ''NLUUG'', ''OOP'', ''PHPNW'', ''SDC'', ''Software Architect'', ''VOXXEDDAYS'', and ''XP Day''.\n\nHenney is a member of the [[Association of C and C Plus Plus Users|ACCU]], and gave the keynote address at the 2001 ACCU conference<ref name=\"ACCU2001\">{{cite web\n |url          = http://thad.notagoth.org/accu_spring_2001/#minimalism\n |title        = ACCU Spring Conference 2001 Roundup\n |author       = Thaddaeus Frogley\n |work         = Thad's Homepage\n |accessdate   = 2005-11-16\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20080514125419/http://thad.notagoth.org/accu_spring_2001/#minimalism#minimalism\n |archive-date = 14 May 2008\n |url-status     = dead\n |df           = dmy-all\n}}</ref> on the subject of writing less code, because \"there is no code faster than no code\" and \"less code, equals less bugs\" (of which he is an active presenter). He is also a speaker at [[OOPSLA]], most recently speaking at OOPSLA 2005.<ref name=\"OOPSLA2005\">{{cite web|\nurl=http://www.enterpriseintegrationpatterns.com/ramblings/37_oopsla.html|\nwork=Gregor's Ramblings|\ntitle=Revenge of the Nerds \u2013 OOPSLA 2005|\naccessdate=2005-11-16}}\n</ref> In October 2009, Henney presented ''The Uncertainty Principle''<ref name=\"PHPNW09\">[http://conference.phpnw.org.uk/phpnw09/?page_id=7 The Uncertainty Principle, Kevlin Henney, 2nd Annual PHP North West Conference]</ref> at the 2nd Annual PHP North West Conference in Manchester, UK. He has also credited with the remark \"...except for the problem of too many layers of indirection\"{{citation needed|date=November 2018}} in response to the famous [[aphorism]] of [[David Wheeler (computer scientist)|David Wheeler]]: \"All problems in computer science can be solved by another level of indirection.\"<ref>Diomidis Spinellis.\n[http://www.dmst.aueb.gr/dds/pubs/inbook/beautiful_code/html/Spi07g.html Another level of indirection].\nIn Andy Oram and Greg Wilson, editors,\n''Beautiful Code: Leading Programmers Explain How They Think'', chapter 17, pages 279&ndash;291.\nO'Reilly and Associates, Sebastopol, CA, 2007.\n</ref>\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* {{cite book|\nauthor=Frank Buschmann|\nauthor2=Kevlin Henney|\nauthor3=Douglas C. Schmidt|\nauthor3-link=Douglas C. Schmidt|\ntitle=Pattern-Oriented Software Architecture, Volume 4: A Pattern Language for Distributed Computing|\nisbn=978-0-470-05902-9|\npublisher=John Wiley & Sons|\nyear=2007}}\n* {{cite book|\nauthor=Frank Buschmann|\nauthor2=Kevlin Henney|\nauthor3=Douglas C. Schmidt|\nauthor3-link=Douglas C. Schmidt|\ntitle=Pattern-Oriented Software Architecture, Volume 5: On Patterns and Pattern Languages|\npublisher=John Wiley & Sons|\nisbn=978-0-471-48648-0|\nyear=2007}}\n* {{cite book|\neditor=Kevlin Henney|\ntitle=97 Things Every Programmer Should Know|\npublisher=O'Reilly Media|\ni